node.text:
Please watch this before you hire a moving company!!! 

On June 17th, 2021, we were moved out of our home in Idaho and were forced to pay our moving company more than triple the quoted amount. Today, we have paid them over $80K, and are still missing more than $40K worth of belongings. 

They have stopped answering our calls and texts and we have hired lawyers. But we are sharing this story so others can be wiser and more educated about the moving industry than we were. There were many red flags along the way that we didn't know to look for. And many moments that we were so panicked and stressed and vulnerable where we were taken advantage of and forced to pay cash and even more money. 

Our hope is that this message, although ongoing and embarrassing for us, will help protect others making major moves and life changes from predators in the moving industry.

node.text: We put together a little montage video of renovating our modern cottage over the last two years and it makes me tear up seeing where we started and how far we’ve come. I see that there are so many memories—really happy memories here. Living in a construction zone is not easy, but to me it was all worth it and even meant to be. #cljmoderncottage

node.text: 🚩🚩After we shared how we got scammed by our moving company a few weeks ago, we received hundreds of similar stories from you, your loved ones, people you know. It's rampant. And the only way it's going to stop is if we stop hiring these people! Specific company names won't help (because they dissolve and start new companies and do the same thing--ours was accredited with great reviews), but looking out for these red flags will!! 🚩🚩Today on chrislovesjulia.com, we've made a list of ten red flags we wish we knew about and sharing details on what you can do if you find yourself in a similar situation. link in profile.

node.text:
My 7 year old and I have been reading Where The Sidewalk Ends before bed. The first  poem in the book is burned in me—Invitation. 

If you are a dreamer, come in,
If you are a dreamer, a wisher, a liar,
A hope-er, a pray-er, a magic bean buyer...
If you're a pretender, come sit by my fire
For we have some flaxgolden tales to spin.
Come in! Come in!

I strive for this space I’ve been carving out for the last 12 years to be an open door for everyone. A front row seat to learning to love where you live. To glean inspiration by watching us make design choices in our home for our family. To learn when we make mistakes and course correct.  Maybe you love what Chris and I are doing with a certain spot. Maybe there have been times when you’ve decided to sneak out and come back later. And certainly there have been times where we have done something you would never do. We still say, “Come in! You’re welcome here!”

Lately, I’ve been feeling the weight of that open invitation. There has so much negativity. A lot of personal attacks. A lot of hateful messages. A lot of blocked people and a lot of hurtful things said about me that you accidentally sent to me instead of your friend. Mostly, I’m happy and confident, but I’m also a real person with real feelings.

I’m a real person that’s reading all of your comments and messages. I’m a real person that’s writing all of the posts for the last 12 years. So let’s just go with the rule: If you wouldn’t say it to my face, then no need to type it out. Because on my end, it feels like you’re saying it to my face. It hurts the same.

There’s no room in your life to hate-follow anyone. If there’s someone that you’re following that makes you rage-y—stop. I want this to a, happy, inspiring place. Where you can be you and I can be me. I want this to be a place where we can celebrate differences and learn. Where we can make mistakes without fear. Where differences in taste don’t turn into callous remarks about my voice, my personality, my preferences. I may not be for you, and that’s ok. For everyone else:

If you are a dreamer, a wisher, a liar,
